[1]
Date: Sun, 19 May 2002 17:37:22 EDT
From: Carolyn Cramoy <Cramoy@aol.com>

Methemoglobinemia has long been a concern of nutritionists involved in
infant feeding. Infants younger than 6 months are particularly susceptible
to methemoglobinemia arising from well water high in nitrites and from the
development of nitrites in vegetables high in nitrates such as beets,
spinach, and carrots. Parents are warned not to feed these foods to infants
younger than 6 months, and never to save pureed spinach, beets, and carrots
or carrot juice in the refrigerator for later use, as bacteria in the food
can cause nitrates to rapidly convert to nitrites. Commercially prepared
spinach, beets, and carrots have been shown to be safe when first opened,
but should not be saved for later use once opened.
Preserved meats such as ham, lunch meats, bacon, and hot dogs are high in
nitrates and nitrites and should never be pureed and added to baby food for
young infants. Further, foods containing these products should not be saved
in the refrigerator for older infants.
Well water, particularly from shallow farm wells, should be checked for
nitrite content before being given to infants for drinking or being used to
prepare infant formula, juice, or food.
--
Carolyn Cramoy MS
Nutritionist
Lake Placid, NY
<cramoy@aol.com>
