Date: Mon, 20 May 2002 14:35:48 -0400
From: James Trostle <james.trostle@mail.cc.trincoll.edu>

If this is truly a case of sodium nitrite poisoning it bears an eerie
resemblance to an incident in New York City in 1944, source of Berton
Roueche's famous article in the New Yorker Magazine (and 1953 collection)
entitled "Eleven Blue Men." In that incident homeless elderly men in NYC
consumed sodium nitrite mistakenly placed by a cook into a vat of oatmeal
and a salt shaker. One man died.
--
James Trostle PhD MPH
Associate Professor of Anthropology
Trinity College
Hartford, CT
and Research Professor
National Institute of Public Health
Mexico
<james.trostle@mail.cc.trincoll.edu>
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Many thanks to those who have recalled Berton Roueche's "Eleven Blue Men"
(we are endebted also to David Sencer <djud2@mindspring.com>, Dean Cliver
<docliver@ucdavis.edu>, and Richard Wilsnac <rwilsnac@medicine.nodak.edu>).
Berton Roueche wrote a series of medical detective stories for the "Annals
in Medicine" column of the New Yorker. His story Eleven Blue Men (from the
Annals in Medicine, and also published in a book called "The Medical
Detectives") described an outbreak of methemoglobinemia in alcoholics in
New York City. A copy of the story (with the author's name spelt
differently) can be found at <http://www.wsu.edu:8080/~shier/BlueMen.html>.
- Mod.MPP]
